'''Genecology''' is a branch of [[ecology]] which studies [[genetic variation]] of [[species]] and [[Community|communities]] compared to their [[population distribution]] in a particular [[Environment (biophysical)|environment]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/genecology | title=genecology | accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=Robert|date=1 October 1979|title=Genecology of Douglas-Fir in a Watershed in the Oregon Cascades|url=|journal=Ecological Society of America|volume=60|issue=5|pages=1036–1050|doi=10.2307/1936871}}</ref> It is closely related to [[ecogenetics]], but genecology focuses primarily on an ecological perspective, looking at changes and interactions between species, while ecogenetics focuses more on species' genetic responses to the environment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Langlet|first=Olof|date=1971-01-01|title=Two Hundred Years Genecology|jstor=1218596|journal=Taxon|volume=20|issue=5/6|pages=653–721|doi=10.2307/1218596}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=TURESSON|first=GöTE|date=February 1923|title=THE SCOPE AND IMPORT OF GENECOLOGY|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1601-5223.1923.tb02955.x/epdf|journal=Hereditas|volume=4|issue=1-2|pages=171–176|doi=10.1111/j.1601-5223.1923.tb02955.x}}</ref>

