{{primary sources|date=June 2016}} {{About|the energy information company||Platts (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox company | name = S&P Global Platts | logo = S&P_Global_Platts.jpg | type = [[Division (business)|Division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.platts.com/about|title=About us|publisher=Platts}}</ref> | former_name = Platts | foundation = [[Cleveland]], Ohio, US ({{Start date and age|1909}}) | founder = Warren C. Platt | area_served = | key_people = Martin Fraenkel – president<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.platts.com/leadership|title=Leadership team|publisher= Platts}}</ref> | industry = [[Energy]], [[Commodities]], [[Oil & Gas]], [[Petrochemicals]], [[Metals]], [[Agriculture]] | products = | services = Commodities & Energy Information and Analytics | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | owner = | num_employees =Approx. 1,000 | parent = [[S&P Global, Inc.]] | divisions = | subsid = | slogan = | homepage = https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en | footnotes = | location_city = London | location_country = The United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.platts.com/office|title=Office locations and contact details|publisher=Platts}}</ref> | location = | dissolved = }}
'''S&P Global Platts''' is a provider of energy and commodities information and a source of [[benchmark price]] assessments in the physical [[energy market]]s. The business was started with the foundation in 1909 of the magazine ''National Petroleum News'' by Warren C. Platt.<ref name=plattshistory/>
S&P Global Platts and [[Argus Media]] are recognized as the two most significant price reporting agencies for the oil market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iosco.org/library/pubdocs/pdf/IOSCOPD364.pdf |title = Oil Price Reporting Agencies: Report by IEA, IEF, OPEC and IOSCO to G20 Finance Ministers | publisher=Jointly published by [[International Energy Agency]], [[International Energy Forum]], [[OPEC]] and [[International Organization of Securities Commissions]] |date=October 2011| p=3}}</ref>
==Overview== From an original focus on the oil industry, S&P Global Platts gradually expanded its purview to include [[metals]], shipping, and all energy-related markets – [[oil]], [[coal]], [[natural gas]], [[electricity]], [[nuclear power]], [[petrochemicals]], [[renewables]], and [[exhaust gas|emissions]]. S&P Global Platts is a division of [[S&P Global, Inc.]], ({{nyse|SPGI}}), a provider of ratings, benchmarks and analytics to the global capital and commodity markets. The firm is sister to brands like S&P Global Ratings, [[S&P Global Market Intelligence]] and [[S&P Dow Jones Indices]]. It had been part of the Commodities & Commercial group of S&P Global, but that group saw all its assets, besides Platts, slowly sold off. It is now considered a stand-alone division of S&P Global, though its President Martin Fraenkel reports into Mike Chinn, the head of S&P Global's Market Intelligence group. <ref>http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/martin-fraenkel-named-president-of-sp-global-platts-300336487.html</ref>
==History== Warren C. Platt (1883–1963) started the magazine ''National Petroleum News'' in [[Cleveland]], Ohio in 1909. He expanded the business with the publication of the newsletter called ''Platts Oilgram'' in 1923, which went on to be recognized as an influential source for petroleum prices. The companies founded by Platt that published prices and news were acquired in 1953 to become part of what was then known as McGraw-Hill group, which was later to become S&P Global. The publication activities that started with petroleum later expanded to cover energy and commodities, which were all undertaken by the division that became known as Platts.<ref name="platts historical">{{cite web| url=http://www.platts.com/IM.Platts.Content/AboutPlatts/Platts%20History-Full%20Summary_5-08-09Final_pdf.pdf| title=Platts – An Historical Perspective| publisher=S&P Global| date=May 2009| accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref>
In 2000 McGraw-Hill merged Platts with other like assets to turn the company into a provider of energy information.<ref name="plattshistory">{{cite web| title=Platts History| url=http://www.platts.com/PlattsHistory.aspx| publisher=S&P Global| accessdate=February 22, 2010 }}</ref>
Beginning in 2010, Platts' parent has made numerous acquisitions to significantly grow the Platts business. The acquired companies were Bentek<ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2010/121410</ref>, Eclipse Energy <ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2014/071714</ref>, Kingsman <ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2012/101112</ref>, Minerals Value Service <ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2015/030315</ref>, RigData <ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2016/060216</ref> and PIRA <ref>https://www.platts.com/pressreleases/2016/080416</ref>. An attempt to acquire OPIS in 2011 failed following market objections and Federal Trade Commission resistance. <ref>https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-250826976.html</ref>
Platts' first significant acquisition came in 2001, when it acquired FT Energy. <ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=wUIwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT56&lpg=PT56&dq=platts+to+acquire+FT+energy&source=bl&ots=mahEUGiibI&sig=QHuj-8HjFOj0joXf4Ltt7yCxQ1Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM7NqbmsbWAhVIsFQKHRknC4YQ6AEIMzAD#v=onepage&q=platts%20to%20acquire%20FT%20energy&f=false</ref> That acquisition gave it the Platts Global Energy Awards, considered one of the industry's biggest awards event, held every December in New York. <ref>https://geaweb.platts.com/</ref>
Since 2013, the company has held an annual Platts Global Metals Awards, modeled on the Platts Global Energy Awards. In 2015, these were held in London.<ref name="finalistsannounced">{{cite web| title=Platts Global Metal Awards| url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/finalists-announced-for-2015-platts-global-metals-awards-300051387.html | accessdate=April 29, 2015 }}</ref>
